Oyo State governor, Seyi Makinde, has said that he will officially announce the new Olubadan of Ibadanland tomorrow. Makinde stated this on Saturday at the grand finale of the burial ceremony of the late Olubadan, Oba Saliu Adetunji, held at the Obafemi Awolowo Stadium, Ibadan. The governor said that all issues hindering the announcement and installation of the new Olubadan had been resolved. “This is another victory for Ibadan traditional institution. The process and the system was never broken, so we have reverted to the age long system. The governor said he had received a letter from the Olubadan in Council in respect of the announcement of the new Olubadan.   Motorists shun FCT elections to queue for fuel     CJN throws open Supreme Court Justice job to lawyers     APC chairmanship: Buhari rejects proposal from two governors   - Advertisement - According to him, Ibadanland has a unique procedure as regards enthronement of new Oba, and this has been in existence for ages. Makinde thanked all Ibadan indigenes and well-wishers that came to witnessed the final burial ceremony. He prayed that Ibadanland would continue to witness more development. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the late Oba Adetunji, who was the 41st Olubadan of Ibadanland, died on January 2 at the age of 93. In a tribute to the late Olubadan, President Muhammadu Buhari described him as a visionary and compassionate leader who used the spheres of his influence to advance the progress of his people. “We trust that the process of selecting his successor will be guided by wisdom, understanding and good judgment that exemplified the life he lived,” the President said. SPONSORED